sitting senators and governors are falling for something very stupid:

several specialty work visa applications must submit something called an LCA to the department of labor, and DOL inputs these into a public database when they stamp an LCA as meeting the “prevailing wages”

the DHS’ own report says that even the 25th percentile H1B visaholder makes 90k a year, median 120. even though all evidence suggests otherwise, there is no way to rule out that the cashier got the visa because @DHSgov doesn’t make their full visa data a matter of public record

and yes a cashier job application can have a correct number on it to be called a prevailing wage by DoL

in the next stage USCIS declines this application with great prejudice because these H1B visas are supposed to go to specialized degree holders.
DHS/USCIS should make all this employment data de-identified and fully public so Governors and Senators can stop having a conniption over visas going to cashiers
